Moments of Symmetry

music theory
tuning

December 10, 2021

"I know it's a drag, babys, to be brought down by pseudo-erudite [...] rantings on mantissi of logs base 2 and all that Jazz --- when all we really want to do is make way out sounds. But there is a little dirty work to be done before we can all get stoned on harmonics, so here we go --- like a herd of turtles, ugh!" - Erv Wilson

The above quote is a nice reminder to the fellow scholars of tuning theory that all we want is to make way out sounds and get stoned on harmonics. The good news is, that most of the dirty work is already done by people like Erv Wilson, who paved the way for microtonal music.

In this post, I want to take a look at one of the most important contributions of Erv Wilson: Moments of Symmetry.

Linear Tuning Systems

Moments of Symmetry (from now on called MOS) is a subset of linear tuning systems with certain properties. A linear tuning system is a system that is generated from a single interval. For example, 3 Limit Just Intonation creates linear tuning systems, because it uses only the number 3 (fifth):

intervals=[30,31,...,3n]intervals = [3^0, 3^1, ..., 3^n]intervals=[30,31,...,3n]

Here, we generate intervals by powers of 3. In a linear tuning system we do the same, but we can use any generator:

intervals=[g0,g1,...,gn]intervals = [g^0, g^1, ..., g^n]intervals=[g0,g1,...,gn]

In code, this can be done with:

function linearTuning(g, n) {
  return Array.from({ length: n }, (_, i) => Math.pow(g, i));
}

Octave reduction

To get a usable tuning system, the numbers are octave reduced, as already described in 3 Limit Just Intonation. In short we can octavate any number between 1 and 2 with this function:

octaveReduce(r)=⌈log⁡2(r−1)⌉octaveReduce(r) = \lceil\log_2 ({r^{-1}})\rceiloctaveReduce(r)=⌈log2​(r−1)⌉

... or with code:

function octaveReduce(ratio) {
  const exp = Math.ceil(Math.log(1 / r) / Math.log(2));
  return Math.pow(2, exp) * ratio;
}
